{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/What is Hadoop and it's Components/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"yusufunlu","author":"Yusuf Unlu"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"994a916e-8b59-5c6e-8268-4ea956ea5621","html":"<p>Hadoop is an open-source software framework that provides distributed storage and processing for massive datasets across computer clusters.</p>\n<p>In the early 2000s, while Yahoo was working on the Apache Nutch open-source web crawler (though I‚Äôm not sure if Nutch was under Apache at that time), Google published influential papers around 2003‚Äì2004 on GFS (Google File System) and MapReduce. Inspired by these, Yahoo developed Hadoop and released it as an open-source project.</p>\n<p>Here‚Äôs an interesting detail: Doug Cutting, who made the largest contributions to Hadoop (while working at Yahoo), is also the creator of Apache Nutch and Lucene. Lucene is another open-source project under the Apache umbrella and forms the core of both Elasticsearch and Solr. The name ‚ÄúHadoop‚Äù comes from Doug Cutting‚Äôs son‚Äôs yellow toy elephant, which also inspired Hadoop‚Äôs logo and mascot.</p>\n<p>Considering Doug Cutting‚Äôs involvement in Lucene, Nutch, Solr, Elasticsearch, and Hadoop, it‚Äôs fair to say these tools share similar architectural patterns and technical approaches.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/10852cd060ddde3764719343760e6d88/e5166/apache_lucene.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 590px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 133.1081081081081%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"I happened to be reading the Lucene book lately üòÑ\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/10852cd060ddde3764719343760e6d88/1c72d/apache_lucene.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/10852cd060ddde3764719343760e6d88/a80bd/apache_lucene.jpg 148w,\n/blog/static/10852cd060ddde3764719343760e6d88/1c91a/apache_lucene.jpg 295w,\n/blog/static/10852cd060ddde3764719343760e6d88/1c72d/apache_lucene.jpg 590w,\n/blog/static/10852cd060ddde3764719343760e6d88/a8a14/apache_lucene.jpg 885w,\n/blog/static/10852cd060ddde3764719343760e6d88/fbd2c/apache_lucene.jpg 1180w,\n/blog/static/10852cd060ddde3764719343760e6d88/e5166/apache_lucene.jpg 1200w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>Now, back to our topic. Google‚Äôs GFS introduced a distributed file system, which inspired the creation of the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS). Similarly, Google‚Äôs MapReduce paper became the foundation for Hadoop‚Äôs MapReduce component. The names have remained almost unchanged.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"apache-flume\"><a href=\"#apache-flume\" aria-hidden class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Apache Flume</h2>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/8ce83c82f6393451937535094f1e2738/04472/flume-logo.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 170px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 100%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"Flume Logo :D\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/8ce83c82f6393451937535094f1e2738/04472/flume-logo.png\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/8ce83c82f6393451937535094f1e2738/12f09/flume-logo.png 148w,\n/blog/static/8ce83c82f6393451937535094f1e2738/04472/flume-logo.png 170w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 170px) 100vw, 170px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    <br>\nFlume is commonly used to collect logs from various sources and write them to HDFS. During this pipeline, data can be filtered or aggregated. While typically used for log data, it can also handle other sources such as emails or network traffic.</p>\n<p>Flume operates using three core concepts:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Source</strong>: where the data comes from</li>\n<li><strong>Channel</strong>: where data is processed or held</li>\n<li><strong>Sink</strong>: where the data goes</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You can send data from a source like an Avro client to HDFS without writing a single line of code. Kafka and Storm can also be used together to achieve what Flume does.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"apache-pig\"><a href=\"#apache-pig\" aria-hidden class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Apache Pig</h2>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/5afb66a1b0469b0885fe4f08e7c81f3a/98fe2/pig-logo.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 269px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 59.45945945945946%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"Pig Logo :D\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/5afb66a1b0469b0885fe4f08e7c81f3a/98fe2/pig-logo.png\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/5afb66a1b0469b0885fe4f08e7c81f3a/12f09/pig-logo.png 148w,\n/blog/static/5afb66a1b0469b0885fe4f08e7c81f3a/98fe2/pig-logo.png 269w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 269px) 100vw, 269px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    <br>\nPig is a platform for analyzing large datasets, using a scripting language called Pig Latin. These scripts are internally converted into MapReduce jobs and typically run on Tez.</p>\n<p>It works with pre-structured data and can extract, transform, and load (ETL) data from various sources into HDFS. Pig can be run via a shell, UI, or Java-based server classes.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"apache-spark\"><a href=\"#apache-spark\" aria-hidden class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Apache Spark</h2>\n<p>Spark is a general-purpose and fast computation engine that can use HDFS for storage. It supports ETL, machine learning, stream processing, and graph analytics. It provides an acyclic (non-looping) dataflow model and can run with or without Hadoop‚Äôs YARN. Spark also supports in-memory caching for performance.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"mapreduce\"><a href=\"#mapreduce\" aria-hidden class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>MapReduce</h2>\n<p>MapReduce is a programming model used for distributed data processing in a Hadoop cluster. It transforms and reduces data using mapper and reducer functions. It‚Äôs fault-tolerant ‚Äî monitored by Hadoop, and jobs are restarted by the application master on failure.<br>\nWhile still used by Hive and Pig, it‚Äôs often avoided today due to its batch-oriented nature.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"apache-hive\"><a href=\"#apache-hive\" aria-hidden class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Apache Hive</h2>\n<p>Hive provides a data warehouse infrastructure and supports ad-hoc queries and data summarization. It offers an SQL-like engine that generates MapReduce jobs and typically runs on Tez. It enables interactive querying and is often used with tools like Impala or Hue.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"apache-tez\"><a href=\"#apache-tez\" aria-hidden class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Apache Tez</h2>\n<p>Tez is an execution framework that provides a more efficient alternative to MapReduce, especially for tools like Hive and Pig. It supports acyclic dataflows and in-memory caching, uses YARN, and allows multiple reduce phases without corresponding map phases ‚Äî improving performance.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"hbase\"><a href=\"#hbase\" aria-hidden class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>HBase</h2>\n<p>HBase is a scalable NoSQL key/value database designed for Hadoop. It supports very large tables and runs on top of YARN. It‚Äôs commonly used for real-time read/write access to big data.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"yarn-yet-another-resource-negotiator\"><a href=\"#yarn-yet-another-resource-negotiator\" aria-hidden class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>YARN (Yet Another Resource Negotiator)</h2>\n<p>YARN is a cluster resource manager and job scheduler. It supports fault tolerance by restarting failed application masters or moving them to another node. Traditional MapReduce is built into YARN. Tools like Storm and Impala directly use YARN. It can also support high availability via Zookeeper with hot standby modes.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2 id=\"other-technologies-to-be-expanded\"><a href=\"#other-technologies-to-be-expanded\" aria-hidden class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Other Technologies (To be expanded):</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Kafka</strong>: Distributed messaging system</li>\n<li><strong>Flink</strong>: Stream processing engine</li>\n<li><strong>Sqoop</strong>: Data transfer between RDBMS and Hadoop</li>\n<li><strong>Zookeeper</strong>: Coordination and configuration service</li>\n<li><strong>Nifi</strong>: Dataflow automation tool</li>\n<li><strong>Storm</strong>: Real-time computation system</li>\n<li><strong>Drill</strong>, <strong>Presto</strong>, <strong>Druid</strong>, <strong>Apex</strong>: Query engines and real-time analytics platforms</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<p>Let me know if you‚Äôd like help turning this into a fully styled Markdown blog post with navigation, images, or side notes for readers.</p>","timeToRead":4,"frontmatter":{"title":"What is Hadoop?","date":"July 25, 2020","spoiler":"Core and optional components of Hadoop and their functions"},"fields":{"slug":"/What is Hadoop and it's Components/","langKey":"en"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/What is Hadoop and it's Components/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/Neo4J Graph Db/","langKey":"en","directoryName":"Neo4J Graph Db","maybeAbsoluteLinks":[]},"frontmatter":{"title":"Neo4J Graph Db nedir ve Spring ile √∂rnek"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/Spring Circuit Breaker/","langKey":"en","directoryName":"Spring Circuit Breaker","maybeAbsoluteLinks":[]},"frontmatter":{"title":"Spring Circuit Breaker"}},"translations":["tr"],"translatedLinks":[]}},"staticQueryHashes":["336482444"]}